## Code Review

### 1. CORS Misconfiguration (Security Issue)

```javascript
app.use(cors({ origin: '*' }));
```

**What's wrong:**
- Allows **any domain** to make requests to your API
- Enables cross-origin requests from malicious websites
- When combined with `credentials: true`, browsers will reject it anyway, creating a false sense of security
- Violates principle of least privilege

**Fix:**
```javascript
// Option 1: Explicit allowlist
const allowedOrigins = [
  'https://yourdomain.com',
  'https://app.yourdomain.com'
];

app.use(cors({
  origin: (origin, callback) => {
    // Allow requests with no origin (mobile apps, curl, Postman)
    if (!origin) return callback(null, true);

    if (!allowedOrigins.includes(origin)) {
      return callback(new Error(`CORS policy violation: origin ${origin} not allowed`));
    }
    return callback(null, true);
  },
  methods: ['GET', 'POST', 'PUT', 'DELETE'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Content-Type', 'Authorization'],
  credentials: true,
  maxAge: 86400 // Cache preflight for 24 hours
}));

// Option 2: Environment-based
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(',') ?? [],
  credentials: true
}));
```

